    contentBody: `Easter is the most important holiday in the Christian calendar, celebrating the resurrection of Jesus Christ from the dead, as described in the New Testament of the Bible. Unlike most holidays, Easter does not fall on a fixed date. It is observed on the first Sunday following the first full moon after the spring equinox, which means it can fall anywhere between March 22 and April 25. In 2026, Easter falls on Sunday, April 5.

The religious observance of Easter is preceded by Lent, a 40-day period of fasting, prayer, and penitence that begins on Ash Wednesday. Holy Week, the final week of Lent, includes Palm Sunday, Maundy Thursday, and Good Friday, each commemorating events from the final days of Jesus's life. Easter Sunday services are among the best-attended church services of the year, with many congregations holding sunrise services, special music programs, and celebratory worship.

Secular Easter traditions are widely enjoyed by both religious and non-religious families. The Easter Bunny, a folkloric figure originating from German Lutheran immigrants in the 1700s, is said to bring baskets filled with candy, chocolate eggs, and small gifts to children on Easter morning. Easter egg hunts are a staple activity, with families hiding decorated eggs in yards and parks for children to find.

Egg decorating is a creative tradition that brings families together in the days leading up to Easter. Hard-boiled eggs are dyed in vibrant colors using commercial kits or natural dyes made from ingredients like onion skins, beets, and turmeric. More elaborate techniques include wax-resist designs, decoupage, and hand-painting. The White House Easter Egg Roll, held on the South Lawn, is one of the oldest annual events in White House history, dating back to 1878.

Easter dinner is a significant meal in many households. Traditional menu items include ham, lamb, deviled eggs, hot cross buns, asparagus, and various spring vegetables. Desserts often feature carrot cake, lemon bars, and Easter-themed cookies. The meal is typically a family gathering, with extended family coming together for a mid-afternoon or early evening dinner.

Planning for Easter involves purchasing Easter baskets and candy, buying new spring outfits (Easter dresses and suits are traditional), organizing egg hunts, and preparing the holiday meal. Candy should be purchased at least a week ahead, and popular items like specialty chocolate eggs sell out at many retailers. Church services, especially at large congregations, may require arriving early to find seating.`,
