    contentBody: `Martin Luther King Jr. Day is a federal holiday observed on the third Monday of January each year, honoring the life and legacy of Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., the most prominent leader of the American civil rights movement. In 2027, MLK Day falls on Monday, January 18. The holiday celebrates King's contributions to advancing civil rights, equality, and social justice through nonviolent protest and powerful oratory.

Dr. King was born on January 15, 1929, in Atlanta, Georgia. He rose to prominence during the Montgomery Bus Boycott of 1955-1956 and went on to lead numerous campaigns for desegregation, voting rights, and economic justice. His "I Have a Dream" speech, delivered during the March on Washington on August 28, 1963, remains one of the most iconic addresses in American history. King was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1964 and continued his advocacy until his assassination on April 4, 1968, in Memphis, Tennessee.

The campaign to establish a federal holiday in King's honor began shortly after his death. Congressman John Conyers introduced legislation for the holiday just four days after King's assassination, but it took 15 years of advocacy, petitions, and public pressure before President Ronald Reagan signed the holiday into law on November 2, 1983. The first official MLK Day was observed on January 20, 1986. It took until 2000 for all 50 states to officially observe the holiday.

MLK Day is the only federal holiday designated as a national day of service. The Martin Luther King Jr. Day of Service encourages Americans to volunteer in their communities, turning the holiday into a day of action rather than merely a day off from work and school. Volunteer activities include food drives, neighborhood cleanups, tutoring programs, habitat building, and mentoring initiatives.

Schools, museums, and cultural institutions across the country host special programs and events on MLK Day. Many schools use the holiday as an educational opportunity to teach students about the civil rights movement, nonviolent resistance, and the ongoing pursuit of equality. Museums offer free admission and special exhibits related to King's life and the broader civil rights struggle.

The holiday falls during a period of winter cold in much of the country, but the three-day weekend provides opportunities for community gatherings, indoor events, and reflection. Many cities host commemorative marches, church services, and public readings of King's speeches. The day serves as both a celebration of progress made and a reminder of the work still needed to achieve King's vision of equality and justice.`,
