    contentBody: `Tax Day in the United States falls on April 15, which is the deadline for individuals to file their federal income tax returns with the Internal Revenue Service. In 2026, Tax Day is Wednesday, April 15, unless the IRS announces any extensions. This date is one of the most important financial deadlines of the year, affecting virtually every working American.

The April 15 deadline has been in effect since 1955, when the Internal Revenue Code was revised and the filing date moved from March 15. The extra month was intended to give taxpayers and the IRS more time to process returns as the tax code became increasingly complex. In some years, Tax Day is moved to a later date when April 15 falls on a weekend or coincides with certain holidays, particularly Emancipation Day in Washington, D.C.

Preparing a tax return can range from simple to extremely complex depending on individual circumstances. Taxpayers with straightforward W-2 income may be able to file using free software or the IRS Free File program. Those with self-employment income, investments, rental properties, or complex deductions may need professional assistance from a certified public accountant or enrolled agent. The IRS estimates that taxpayers spend an average of 13 hours preparing their returns.

Key documents needed for tax filing include W-2 forms from employers, 1099 forms for freelance income, interest, and dividends, receipts for deductible expenses, records of charitable contributions, and documentation for any credits claimed. Most employers and financial institutions are required to send these forms by January 31, giving taxpayers about two and a half months to gather documents and prepare their returns.

For those expecting a refund, filing early is advantageous. The IRS typically begins accepting returns in late January, and early filers may receive refunds within 21 days of filing electronically with direct deposit. The average federal tax refund is approximately $3,000, representing a significant financial event for many households.

Taxpayers who cannot meet the April 15 deadline can request an automatic six-month extension by filing IRS Form 4868. However, an extension to file is not an extension to pay. Estimated taxes owed must still be paid by April 15 to avoid penalties and interest. Financial advisors recommend estimating your tax liability and making a payment with the extension request to minimize potential penalties.`,
